    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-09-01T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-09-01T05:00:00-05:00" n="404"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d404">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760C.62/1260: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-09-01T11:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 1, 1939—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 1—7:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>355. I am informed that yesterday the Italian Government made another effort to
                    avoid disaster. During the morning Ciano<note n="4" xml:id="d404fn4">Count
                        Galeazzo Ciano di Cortellazzo, Italian Minister for Foreign Affairs.</note>
                    proposed to the British Ambassador the calling of a conference of various
                    European powers including Poland to consider all the clauses of the Treaty of
                        Versailles<note n="5" xml:id="d404fn5">Signed June 28, 1919, <ref
                            target="frus1919Parisv13#pg_55">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, The Paris Peace Conference,
                            1919, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">xiii</hi>, p. 55</ref>.</note> which are
                    the cause of existing European friction. This suggestion was transmitted to
                    London and through London to Paris. I learn from the British Embassy that no
                    official reply has yet been given. Daladier<note n="6" xml:id="d404fn6">Édouard
                        Daladier, President of the French Council of Ministers and Minister for
                        National Defense.</note> is understood to have told Phipps<note n="7"
                        xml:id="d404fn7">Sir Eric Phipps, British Ambassador in France.</note> that
                    he personally is strongly opposed to such a conference.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
